WEBVTT

00:01.000 --> 00:03.000
Trade in the Gulf and beyond.

00:06.000 --> 00:10.000
Long before today's skyscrapers and oil tankers,

00:10.000 --> 00:13.000
the Gulf region was already a center of trade.

00:13.000 --> 00:21.000
Over 4,000 years ago, between 2,600 BCE and 1,900 BCE,

00:21.000 --> 00:26.000
one of the world's earliest civilizations, the Indus Valley Civilization,

00:26.000 --> 00:29.000
was actively trading with ancient Gulf communities.

00:30.000 --> 00:34.000
Located in what is now Pakistan and Northwest India,

00:34.000 --> 00:38.000
the Indus people built advanced cities like Harapa,

00:38.000 --> 00:40.000
Mohenjo Daro, and Lothal.

00:40.000 --> 00:44.000
Lothal featured one of the world's oldest known dockyards,

00:44.000 --> 00:48.000
enabling maritime trade across the Arabian Sea.

00:48.000 --> 00:51.000
Archaeological evidence shows that

00:51.000 --> 00:54.000
Indus traders reach Mesopotamia and the Gulf,

00:54.000 --> 00:57.000
including Dillman, modern-day Bahrain,

00:57.000 --> 01:02.000
a trading hub mentioned in Sumerian text as a land of purity and commerce.

01:02.000 --> 01:07.000
Goods like copper, cotton textile, and bread were exchanged

01:07.000 --> 01:11.000
for lapis lazuli, dates, and silver.

01:11.000 --> 01:16.000
Indus seals found at Gulf sites such as Umalnar, UAE,

01:16.000 --> 01:21.000
and Ross Aljins, Oman, proved these connections.

01:21.000 --> 01:24.000
Trade wasn't just about goods,

01:24.000 --> 01:27.000
it also enabled the exchange of technology,

01:27.000 --> 01:30.000
like boat design and standard weights,

01:30.000 --> 01:35.000
indicating the early flow of ideas between civilizations.

01:35.000 --> 01:38.000
Today's Gulf economy still depend on trade,

01:38.000 --> 01:41.000
but it all started with early seed links,

01:41.000 --> 01:44.000
like those with the Indus Valley.

